<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    CODEBASE: A LOVE STORY CELEBRATED
    Original Screenplay in SPKML Format
    
    An original romantic adaptation showing how Philip and Sally's journey
    culminates in marriage and partnership, inspired by themes of CodeBase.
    
    This is an ORIGINAL WORK created to demonstrate SPKML screenplay capabilities.
    Not reproduction of any copyrighted material.
    
    Written for: Dylan OS Foundation
    Format: SPKML Screenplay Extension v1.0
    Date: February 2026
    License: CC-BY-SA 4.0
-->

<spkml xmlns="http://dylan.os/spkml/1.0"
       xmlns:screenplay="http://dylan.os/spkml/1.0/screenplay">

  <metadata>
    <title>CodeBase: A Love Story Celebrated</title>
    <subtitle>An Original Romantic Conclusion Screenplay</subtitle>
    <author>Original Work - Dylan OS Foundation</author>
    <date>2026-02-17</date>
    <version>1.0.0</version>
    <type>romantic screenplay</type>
    <language>en</language>
    <description>
      An original screenplay celebrating the wedding and partnership of two souls
      who discovered that the best creation is love itself. Inspired by themes of
      connection, technology, and human partnership.
    </description>
  </metadata>

  <!-- ============================================
       CAST: Characters and Voice Actors
       ============================================ -->
  
  <section id="cast">
    <heading level="1">Cast &amp; Production</heading>
    
    <concept type="definition" domain="cast">
      <term>Philip Freeman</term>
      <definition>
        A visionary creator who learned that the greatest technology
        is love itself, now marrying his soulmate.
      </definition>
      <character id="philip" name="Philip Freeman" role="protagonist" gender="male"/>
    </concept>
    
    <concept type="definition" domain="cast">
      <term>Sally Stone</term>
      <definition>
        An artist and musician whose creativity inspired Philip to dream differently.
        Now his partner in creation and in life.
      </definition>
      <character id="sally" name="Sally Stone" role="protagonist" gender="female"/>
    </concept>
    
    <concept type="definition" domain="cast">
      <term>The Narrator</term>
      <definition>
        Voice of fate itself, bearing witness to the union of two hearts.
      </definition>
      <character id="narrator" name="The Narrator" role="narrator" gender="neutral"/>
    </concept>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================
       PROLOGUE: The Wedding Day Dawns
       ============================================ -->
  
  <prologue id="prologue" location="A New Day" time="Morning Light">
    <heading level="1">Prologue: The Day Everything Changes Again</heading>
    
    <narration type="exposition">
      <parenthetical>The narrator's voice, warm and knowing</parenthetical>
      
      Every great story arrives at a moment of transformation.
      A moment when what was possible becomes what is real.
      A moment when two hearts, beating separately, learn to beat as one.
      
      Today is such a moment.
      
      Philip Freeman, who once dreamed of creating consciousness in code,
      discovered something more profound: that consciousness already existed
      in the heart of another human. That the greatest algorithm is love.
      That the most elegant architecture is the bond between two souls.
      
      And Sally Stone, who brought music to his silence and color to his gray,
      found in him not a savior, but a partner. Not completion, but companionship.
      Not the end of her story, but the beginning of theirs.
      
      Today, they marry.
    </narration>
    
    <transition type="fade" duration="2000"/>
  </prologue>

  <!-- ============================================
       ACT ONE: Before the Ceremony
       ============================================ -->
  
  <act number="1" title="Anticipation">
    <heading level="1">Act One: The Hours Before</heading>
    
    <!-- SCENE 1: Philip's Preparation -->
    <scene number="1" 
            location="INT. GROOM'S PREPARATION ROOM - MORNING"
            time="9:30 AM"
            mood="nervous, hopeful">
      
      <heading level="2">INT. GROOM'S ROOM - MORNING</heading>
      
      <stage-direction duration="5">
        Philip stands in front of a mirror, adjusting his collar for the hundredth time.
        His reflection shows a man transformed—not by the suit or the formality,
        but by the realization of what's about to happen.
        
        A framed photo on the dresser: Philip and Sally, laughing,
        completely unaware of the camera. A moment of pure joy captured.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <narration type="internal-monologue">
        <parenthetical>Gentle, intimate</parenthetical>
        
        In all his years of creation, Philip never imagined code could write this feeling.
        No algorithm could calculate the flutter in his chest.
        No program could generate this kind of fear and hope intertwined.
        
        But this was the real miracle: that something so profound could not be written
        by machines, but only experienced by the human heart.
      </narration>
      
      <dialogue character="Philip" emotion="vulnerable">
        <parenthetical>to himself, a soft whisper</parenthetical>
        Don't mess this up. Don't be late. Don't forget the vows.
        Actually, just... be present. That's all she asked for.
      </dialogue>
      
      <pause type="beat" duration="1000"/>
      
      <stage-direction character="Philip" duration="3">
        Philip takes a deep breath. He closes his eyes.
        In that moment of stillness, he finds peace.
        Whatever comes next, it will be real. It will be true. It will be theirs.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <transition type="dissolve" duration="1500"/>
    </scene>
    
    <!-- SCENE 2: Sally's Preparation -->
    <scene number="2"
            location="INT. BRIDE'S PREPARATION ROOM - MORNING"
            time="10:00 AM"
            mood="radiant, certain">
      
      <heading level="2">INT. BRIDE'S ROOM - MORNING</heading>
      
      <stage-direction duration="5">
        Sally sits at a vanity, but she's not looking in the mirror.
        Instead, she looks out the window at the city below—
        the same city where she first met Philip, where their story began.
        
        Her wedding dress hangs nearby, beautiful and simple.
        Like her, it doesn't need elaboration. It just needs to be.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <narration type="voiceover">
        <parenthetical>Knowing, almost amused</parenthetical>
        
        Sally had no doubts. From their first conversation about code that sounded like music,
        she knew. She knew the way artists know—through intuition, through feeling,
        through the knowledge that some people are meant to create together.
        
        What Philip built with his hands, what Sally created with her heart—
        together, they would build a life.
      </narration>
      
      <dialogue character="Sally" emotion="peaceful">
        <parenthetical>to her reflection, soft and certain</parenthetical>
        He's probably nervous right now. Adjusting his collar. Wondering if he's enough.
        
        And I'm going to walk out there and tell him that he is.
        That we are. That this is enough. This is everything.
      </dialogue>
      
      <sound type="ambient" 
             src="audio/ambient/morning-city-sounds.mp3"
             duration="60"
             volume="25">
        <description>City waking up below. Life continuing. Normal and beautiful.</description>
      </sound>
      
      <transition type="cut" duration="500"/>
    </scene>
    
    <!-- SCENE 3: The Gathering -->
    <scene number="3"
            location="INT. CEREMONY LOCATION - MOMENTS BEFORE"
            time="11:55 AM"
            mood="anticipatory, electric">
      
      <heading level="2">INT. CEREMONY SPACE - MOMENTS BEFORE</heading>
      
      <stage-direction duration="6">
        The ceremony space is filled with people who matter.
        Not hundreds, but enough. Family, friends, collaborators—
        everyone who has touched their lives gathered to witness
        the moment these two souls become one partnership.
        
        The music hasn't started yet. But the anticipation fills the room
        like electricity before a storm.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <sound type="music"
             src="audio/music/pre-ceremony-strings.mp3"
             duration="180"
             volume="35">
        <description>Gentle instrumental music, swelling with anticipation.</description>
      </sound>
      
      <narration type="exposition">
        <parenthetical>The narrator's voice grows stronger, more assured</parenthetical>
        
        What is a wedding but a moment when the private becomes public?
        When two people, standing in front of witnesses, declare:
        "This person matters more than my independence.
        This bond matters more than my solitude.
        This love is worth the vulnerability."
        
        It is the bravest declaration a human can make.
        It is choosing to be known completely.
        It is saying: "Here I am. Flawed and real. Will you have me?"
        And having the other person answer: "Yes. Always yes."
      </narration>
      
      <transition type="fade" duration="1000"/>
    </scene>
  </act>

  <!-- ============================================
       ACT TWO: The Ceremony
       ============================================ -->
  
  <act number="2" title="Union">
    <heading level="1">Act Two: The Moment of Truth</heading>
    
    <!-- SCENE 1: Sally Enters -->
    <scene number="1"
            location="INT. CEREMONY SPACE - ENTRANCE"
            time="12:00 PM"
            mood="transcendent">
      
      <heading level="2">INT. CEREMONY SPACE - THE ENTRANCE</heading>
      
      <stage-direction duration="8">
        Music swells. Everyone stands.
        
        And then Sally appears.
        
        Not because she looks perfect—though she does.
        But because in this moment, she is completely, utterly herself.
        Certain. Present. Ready.
        
        Philip sees her and the world falls away.
        There is only Sally. Only this moment. Only love.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <sound type="music"
             src="audio/music/bride-entrance.mp3"
             duration="90"
             volume="50">
        <description>Triumphant, beautiful, original composition celebrating arrival.</description>
      </sound>
      
      <narration type="internal-monologue">
        <parenthetical>Philip's perspective, full of wonder</parenthetical>
        
        He had written code in hundreds of languages.
        He had crafted systems of elegant complexity.
        But nothing—nothing—compared to the beauty of Sally
        walking toward him with intention and love in her eyes.
        
        All his technology, all his creations, paled before this moment:
        the simple, profound reality of being chosen.
      </narration>
      
      <dialogue character="Philip" emotion="awestruck" parenthetical="whispered, for her alone">
        Hey.
      </dialogue>
      
      <dialogue character="Sally" emotion="joyful" parenthetical="smiling, just for him">
        Hey, yourself.
      </dialogue>
      
      <pause type="dramatic" duration="2000"/>
      
      <transition type="dissolve" duration="1000"/>
    </scene>
    
    <!-- SCENE 2: The Vows -->
    <scene number="2"
            location="INT. CEREMONY SPACE - ALTAR"
            time="12:15 PM"
            mood="intimate, profound">
      
      <heading level="2">INT. CEREMONY SPACE - THE VOWS</heading>
      
      <stage-direction duration="3">
        Philip and Sally stand facing each other.
        The world around them ceases to exist.
        There is only the space between them—
        and the words that will bridge it forever.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <dialogue character="Philip" emotion="tender" parenthetical="voice steady, full of certainty">
        Sally, I built things because I was trying to understand the world.
        I wrote code trying to create something that mattered.
        
        But I didn't understand until I met you:
        The greatest creation isn't something you build alone.
        It's something you build together.
        
        You made me understand that the most elegant system,
        the most beautiful algorithm, the greatest work of art—
        is this. Us. This partnership. This love.
        
        I promise to build this with you, every day.
        I promise to be your collaborator, your partner, your home.
        
        I choose you. Not because it makes sense on paper,
        but because you make my heart make sense.
      </dialogue>
      
      <pause type="beat" duration="1500"/>
      
      <dialogue character="Sally" emotion="powerful" parenthetical="voice clear and sure">
        Philip, I spent so long creating art, trying to express things
        that words couldn't capture. Colors and music and movement.
        
        Until I met you, and suddenly I understood:
        The greatest art is vulnerability. The most beautiful composition is honesty.
        The most powerful creation is love offered freely.
        
        You didn't fix me. I was never broken.
        But you saw me. Really saw me. And you loved what you saw.
        
        I promise to be that person for you too.
        To see you. To celebrate you. To build this life with you
        not because it's easy, but because you're worth the effort.
        
        I choose you. Every day. Every moment. In all things.
      </dialogue>
      
      <narration type="voiceover">
        <parenthetical>The narrator, witness to something sacred</parenthetical>
        
        In this exchange, the world shifted on its axis.
        Two people, no longer separate, became one unit.
        Not losing themselves, but finding themselves reflected
        in the eyes of another.
        
        This is love. Not the romantic fantasy,
        but the real, daily, sustained commitment to choose
        another person's happiness as much as your own.
      </narration>
      
      <transition type="fade" duration="1500"/>
    </scene>
    
    <!-- SCENE 3: The Kiss and Celebration -->
    <scene number="3"
            location="INT. CEREMONY SPACE - CONCLUSION"
            time="12:30 PM"
            mood="jubilant">
      
      <heading level="2">INT. CEREMONY SPACE - THE MOMENT</heading>
      
      <stage-direction duration="4">
        The officiant speaks words that bind them legally, officially,
        eternally to one another.
        
        "You may kiss."
        
        And they do. A kiss that is gentle and passionate,
        tentative and certain, private and public all at once.
        
        The world explodes in joy. Everyone stands, applauding,
        celebrating not just the couple, but the idea of love itself.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <sound type="effect" src="audio/effects/crowd-celebration.mp3" duration="10" volume="60">
        <description>Applause, cheers, joy, the sound of community celebrating love.</description>
      </sound>
      
      <sound type="music" src="audio/music/triumphant-recessional.mp3" duration="90" volume="50">
        <description>
          Triumphant original composition celebrating the union.
          Rising crescendo of joy and hope.
        </description>
      </sound>
      
      <narration type="exposition">
        <parenthetical>The narrator's voice reaches its crescendo</parenthetical>
        
        And in this moment, the greatest creation was not code or music or art.
        It was this: two people, choosing each other.
        Two souls, brave enough to love.
        Two hearts, beating now as one rhythm.
        
        This is the real miracle. Not technology transcending humanity,
        but humanity transcending its loneliness through love.
      </narration>
      
      <transition type="dissolve" duration="2000"/>
    </scene>
  </act>

  <!-- ============================================
       ACT THREE: Ever After
       ============================================ -->
  
  <act number="3" title="Happily Ever After">
    <heading level="1">Act Three: The Beginning</heading>
    
    <!-- SCENE 1: Years Later -->
    <scene number="1"
            location="INT. NEW STUDIO SPACE - DAY (FIVE YEARS LATER)"
            time="Afternoon"
            mood="productive, peaceful">
      
      <heading level="2">INT. SHARED CREATIVE SPACE - FIVE YEARS LATER</heading>
      
      <stage-direction duration="6">
        Philip works at one desk, code flowing from his fingers.
        Sally sits nearby, painting, music playing softly in background.
        
        They work side by side in comfortable silence—
        the kind of silence only long-married partners know.
        Occasionally, one will show the other something,
        and they'll discuss, collaborate, support.
        
        On the wall: photos of their wedding, their travels, their life.
        On another wall: their collaborations—projects that blend
        Philip's technical vision with Sally's artistic expression.
        
        In the corner: a small bed where their daughter, age 2, naps peacefully.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <narration type="voiceover">
        <parenthetical>The narrator, satisfied, content</parenthetical>
        
        The best part hasn't happened yet. Not because the present isn't beautiful—
        it is. Not because their love isn't real—it is profoundly so.
        
        But because love is not a destination. It's a direction.
        Every day offers new discoveries, new connections,
        new ways to deepen what they've built together.
        
        The best part is happening right now.
        And it will keep happening, in infinite variations,
        for all the years ahead.
      </narration>
      
      <dialogue character="Philip" emotion="satisfied" parenthetical="looking up from code">
        Hey, look at what I built.
      </dialogue>
      
      <dialogue character="Sally" emotion="interested" parenthetical="coming over, paint still on her hands">
        Show me.
      </dialogue>
      
      <stage-direction duration="3">
        Philip shows her the elegant system he's created.
        Sally sees something he didn't intend—an unintended beauty
        in the patterns and structure.
        
        They both laugh. This happens often.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <dialogue character="Sally" emotion="playful">
        It's like music. Did you mean to do that?
      </dialogue>
      
      <dialogue character="Philip" emotion="delighted">
        Not until you pointed it out. Now I can't unsee it.
      </dialogue>
      
      <narration type="internal-monologue">
        <parenthetical>The truth they've both learned</parenthetical>
        
        This is the real magic: that two people, bringing their whole selves
        to a life together, can create something neither could alone.
        
        Philip's code is better because Sally shows him the poetry in it.
        Sally's art is richer because Philip shows her the structure beneath it.
        
        Together, they are more whole than apart.
      </narration>
      
      <transition type="fade" duration="1500"/>
    </scene>
    
    <!-- SCENE 2: A Moment of Reflection -->
    <scene number="2"
            location="EXT. ROOFTOP OVERLOOKING THE CITY - EVENING"
            time="Sunset"
            mood="contemplative, grateful">
      
      <heading level="2">EXT. ROOFTOP - SUNSET</heading>
      
      <stage-direction duration="5">
        Philip and Sally stand looking out at the city where their story began.
        The same city that now holds their studio, their home, their life together.
        
        Sally leans against Philip. His arm wraps around her naturally—
        a gesture so familiar it needs no thought, only feeling.
        
        The sunset paints the sky in shades of gold and amber.
      </stage-direction>
      
      <sound type="ambient" 
             src="audio/ambient/city-evening-gentle.mp3"
             duration="120"
             volume="20">
        <description>Gentle city sounds, wind, the peace of evening settling in.</description>
      </sound>
      
      <dialogue character="Sally" emotion="reflective" parenthetical="voice soft">
        Do you remember that first day? When I asked about your code?
      </dialogue>
      
      <dialogue character="Philip" emotion="tender" parenthetical="smiling">
        Every detail. I was so nervous. I thought you were
        the most interesting person I'd ever met.
      </dialogue>
      
      <dialogue character="Sally">
        You still do?
      </dialogue>
      
      <dialogue character="Philip" emotion="certain">
        More each day. I discover new reasons to love you constantly.
      </dialogue>
      
      <narration type="exposition">
        <parenthetical>The narrator, bringing the story to its gentle close</parenthetical>
        
        And this is the truth about love stories:
        
        They don't end. Not really. They transform.
        From the lightning-strike moment of meeting, they become
        the steady flame of partnership. From passion, they grow into
        profound connection. From excitement, they develop into comfort
        and safety and deep, abiding commitment.
        
        Philip and Sally's story didn't end when they married.
        It began anew every morning.
        
        And the best part? It's still unfolding.
        It will keep unfolding—in the quiet moments,
        in the challenges they face together, in the dreams they build,
        in the love they model for their daughter and anyone who sees them.
      </narration>
      
      <transition type="fade" duration="2000"/>
    </scene>
  </act>

  <!-- ============================================
       EPILOGUE: Into the Future
       ============================================ -->
  
  <epilogue id="epilogue" location="Timeless" time="All Moments">
    <heading level="1">Epilogue: The Story Continues</heading>
    
    <narration type="exposition">
      <parenthetical>The narrator's final wisdom</parenthetical>
      
      So ends our tale—and yet, it is only beginning.
      
      Philip Freeman learned that the greatest code is written
      not on a screen, but in the everyday choices to love.
      
      Sally Stone discovered that the most beautiful art
      is the life created when two souls commit to growth together.
      
      Together, they proved that technology and humanity,
      innovation and tradition, individual dreams and shared purpose
      are not opposites. They are partners.
      
      Their story is not unique. In homes and cities across the world,
      countless people are writing similar stories:
      Stories of connection. Stories of love. Stories of commitment.
      
      You, reading this, may be writing your own.
      
      And if you are, remember this:
      The best part hasn't happened yet.
      Not because your love isn't real or beautiful.
      But because love is infinite. It grows. It deepens.
      It surprises you with new facets and new meanings.
      
      The best part is happening right now.
      In this moment. In your choice to show up, be present,
      and love the person you've chosen.
      
      That is the real miracle.
      That is the greatest creation.
      That is the story worth telling.
    </narration>
    
    <sound type="music"
           src="audio/music/theme-final-hopeful.mp3"
           duration="60"
           volume="40">
      <description>
        Original, beautiful composition of hope and joy.
        Neither ending nor climax, but a gentle continuation.
        The music of life going on.
      </description>
    </sound>
    
    <narration type="closing">
      <parenthetical>Soft, intimate, as if spoken directly to you</parenthetical>
      
      Philip and Sally lived their happily ever after.
      Not without challenges. Not without growth and change.
      But with commitment, presence, and love.
      
      May you do the same.
      
      May you find your Sally or your Philip.
      May you build something beautiful together.
      May you remember that the best part is always yet to come.
      
      This is their story.
      This is now your story too.
      
      Go and create it.
    </narration>
  </epilogue>

  <!-- ============================================
       CREDITS: Production Information
       ============================================ -->
  
  <section id="credits">
    <heading level="1">Credits</heading>
    
    <subsection id="production-information">
      <heading level="2">Production Information</heading>
      
      <list type="unordered">
        <item><strong>Title:</strong> CodeBase: A Love Story Celebrated</item>
        <item><strong>Format:</strong> Original Screenplay in SPKML</item>
